<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="591" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,260,1187]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1018,1043]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[326,609,1018,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tribrachyblasta">
<emphasis box="[326,609,1018,1043]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Pedionis tribrachyblasta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Zhang &amp; Viraktamath" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Viraktamath" box="[745,1142,1018,1043]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Pedionis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="591" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yunnana">
<emphasis box="[745,873,1020,1043]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">P. yunnana</emphasis>
Zhang &amp; Viraktamath
</taxonomicName>
externally, but differs in having lighter colour. Pygofer is truncate apically with three dendritic ventral processes, and with several stout setae along subapical ventral margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="591" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1436,260,1187]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1126,1151]" pageId="4" pageNumber="591">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word “tri–” and “brachyblastus”, which refers to the three dendritic processes of the pygofer.
</paragraph>
